<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>The workers told the SunTeam they were told on Wednesday afternoon the factory would remain closed until they received results.The workers said they were concerned that they wouldn’t be paid until the factory opened again. Bheki Shabane, provincial secretary of the United Chemical Industries Mining Electrical State Health and Aligned Workers Union, said the department was taking too long to give them feedback. When the SunTeam contacted factory managing director Nkululeko Luthuli, he said he was busy on another call and would be available in 30 minutes. But he failed to answer when the SunTeam called back. In a letter he gave to workers he said: “Due to the backlog at state laboratories, our results have not been returned. As a result, we have to conduct private testing of our products to ensure safety.”When asked about the delay, KZN Health spokeswoman Samke Khumalo referred the SunTeam to the department’s website. However, the information was not online.